<br>
To find out what the reality is, I had to find out first the GDP of India in nominal terms.  First, I found out the actual GDP of India in terms of its currency, the rupee.  The Indian GDP in terms of rupee in FY 2001 was 20 trillion rupees.  The exchange rate as of  May 14, 2001 was 47 rupees to the dollar.  (In comparison, the exchange rate for rupee-dollar today is 48 to the dollar.)  Therefore, in terms of US dollars, the Indian GDP in nominal terms for 2001 was $.427 trillion.  Presuming the Indian GDP had grown 5% in 2001, the GDP in nominal terms for India in 2000 was probably only $.4 trillion  (presuming the exchange rate had remained the same from 2000 to 2001).  <br>
<br>
Next, I found out the real GDP of China and India in real (PPP) terms.  It was given by the World Bank that the GDP in real terms for China and India in 2000 was $5 trillion and $2 trillion respectively.  Therefore, dividing $2 trillion by $.4 trillion gives the ratio between the real and nominal values of Indian GDP which is 5.  <br>
<br>
Finally, multiplying $15.9 by 5 gives $79.5 billion for India’s real military spending in 2001.  And in terms of percentage, $79.5 billion is 3.9% of $2 trillion.  In other words, India’s military budget for year 2000 was 3.9% of its real GDP.  <br>
<br>
In contrast, China’s GDP in 2000 in yuan terms was 8.9 trillion yuan.  In nominal terms at 8.3 yuan to the dollar this was $1.07 trillion.  Divide $5 trillion by $1.07 trillion gives a ratio of 4.7 between the nominal and real GDP of China.  And multiplying China‘s 2000 military budget in nominal terms which was $14.5 billion by 4.7 gives $68.2 billion as the real value of China military budget for 2000.  And it terms of percentage, $68.2 billion is 1.36% of $5 trillion.  In other words, China’s military budget for 2000 was 1.36% of its real GDP.<br>
<br>
So now we have two sets of real numbers for the military budget of China and India for year 2000:<br>
<br>
China $68.2 billion 1.36% of GDP.<br>
India  $79.5 billion 3.9% of GDP.<br>
<br>
Given India’s weaker economy, it is obvious that it is spending too much on its military budget.  This is obviously one of the reasons that contribute to India’s inability to grow rapidly.  Too much of its resources is being used to maintain a military that is essentially contributing nothing to the development of its economy.  <br>
<br>
In contrast China is spending only 1.36 % of its GDP for military in 2000.  I think this is too little in view of the dangerous enemies that China has.  China should increase its military budget to at least 1.5% of its expanding GDP.  The GDP for 2003 will probably reach 11 trillion yuan.  If 1.5% this is budgeted for the military, the 2003 Chinese military budget will be 165 billion yuan.  In real terms of 1 yuan to $.60, this is some $100 billion.  I hope the Chinese government would budget at least this much for its military spending.  While it is important to develop the economy, yet without a strong military to safeguard the future of China, all the economic advancement will not allow the Chinese people to enjoy an honorable and peaceful life.<br>
